import 'package:http/http.dart' as http;
But the problem is — other packages (or even your own code) might also have a function named get() or post().
That would cause confusion or conflicts.
So we use the alias http. to make it crystal clear where it’s coming from:


🌟 What is a FutureBuilder?
FutureBuilder is a Flutter widget that automatically waits for async data (like API calls, Firebase, file loading, etc.)
and rebuilds the UI when that data arrives.
Think of it like this:
“Hey Flutter, go fetch some data. While waiting, show a loading spinner.
When data arrives, show it. If something fails, show an error.”

We use the http package in Flutter when calling an API because it allows our app to send and receive data over the internet — using the HTTP protocol (like GET, POST, PUT, DELETE).

you cannot just paste raw JSON into Flutter and expect it to work. You need to convert it into Dart objects first.

